== Finding The Number 2. ==
[[File:Complex_unit_circle.png|thumb|right|200px|Finding a number with the length of a=1]]
The easy way to solve this problem is to set the variable to be a imaginary number since the number that satisfy this problem is located on the unit circle.

The first thing we have to do is to express the number in polar form by writing it as,
: <math>z = a\,\cos \theta + a\,i\,\sin \theta</math> where <math>a</math> is the length of the complex number. Since <math>a=1</math>, we can rewrite the number as
: <math>z = \cos \theta + i\sin \theta</math>.

The reason why we want to express the number in this way is to exploit the features of polar form expression of a complex number. The idea is when the characteristics of the equations are expressed as characteristics of the polar form expression, it is easier to identify connections between the two. In this problem it is simpler to look for the solution by looking for <math>\theta</math> instead of <math>z</math>.

To do so, we want to convert every other complex number in the equation to the polar form too. Hence, we have
: <math>z^n = (\cos \theta + i\sin \theta )^n = 1</math>.

Substituting the equation and the form of <math>z</math> into it we get
: <math>(\cos(\theta) + i \sin(\theta))^n = 1</math>. We can go on and convert the equation to polar form but it turns out we don't need to.

Now we can use [[De Moivre's Theorem]] by simply raising the equation to the '''<math>n^{th}</math>''' power.
: <math> (\cos(\theta) + i\sin(\theta))^n = \cos(n \theta) + i \sin(n \theta)</math>.

Hence, we get
: <math>\cos(n \theta) + i \sin(n \theta) = 1</math>.

Notice the fact the we can use [[Euler's Identity]] in the form of
: <math>e^{i\theta} = \cos \theta + i\sin \theta</math>.

Now we can apply it to the previous equation and get
: <math>e^{ni\theta} = e^{2\pi i}</math>.

Using [[Euler's identity]] we get
: <math>e^{ni\theta} = e^{i\theta} \cdot e^{i\theta} \cdot e^{i\theta} \cdot \cdot \cdot e^{i\theta}</math>.

Since we set that <math>e^{i\theta} = 1</math>, the equation reduces to
: <math>e^{ni\theta} = 1</math>.

We can conclude that <math>n\theta = 2\pi i</math>. Solving for <math>\theta</math> gives
: <math>\theta = \frac{2\pi i}{n}</math>.

Now we can add multiples of <math>\theta</math> and the number is still a solution to this equation.

: <math>\frac{2\pi i}{n}, \frac{4\pi i}{n}, \frac{6\pi i}{n},..., \frac{2(k\pi) i}{n}</math> where k is all positive integers.

== Generalization ==
[[File:UnitCirclePowers2.png|250px|right]]
Now we can generalize our findings to any complex number <math>z = a + bi</math> such that <math>|z| = 1</math>. Previously we found the solutions to the equation <math>z^n = 1</math>. We noticed that regardless of the value of <math>n</math>, the solutions to the equation are evenly spread out around the unit circle.

We can now see that this is a true statement because
:<math> |z^n| = |z||z| \cdot \cdot \cdot |z| = |z|^n = 1</math>

We see that the magnitude of <math>z</math> did not change after being multiplied by itself for an arbitrary number of time.

Now we want to extend this thinking and see that when we have the equation
: <math>z^n = z_0</math>

We can divide both side of the equation by <math>|z_0|</math> to get
: <math>z^n = \frac{z_0}{|z_0|}</math>.

We can now see that the new equation satisfy the equation <math>z^n = 1</math> that we began our journey with. Hence, using the same methods as shown above, we can show that the solution to this equation is
: <math>z = \frac{z_0}{|z_0|} (\cos \theta + i \sin \theta)</math> where <math>\theta = \frac{2(k\pi)}{n}</math> and k is all positive integers.

We can also rearrange our equation in polar form to get
: <math>z = \frac{z_0}{|z_0|} (\cos \theta + i \sin \theta)</math>
: <math>z = \frac{z_0}{|z_0|} e^{i\theta}</math> where <math>\theta = \frac{2(k\pi)}{n}</math> and k is all positive integers.

=Why It's Interesting=

The equation <math>z^n = z_0</math> is a [[Mandelbrot Set|''Mandelbrot'' like]] equation with <math>n = 2</math>. The Julia Set of the Mandelbrot set with <math>n = 2</math> would be the unit circle.

We assume that all variables and parameters, such as the mean and variance, take real values. The only exception is the categorical parameter, which is a list of strings. The categorical parameter only makes sense for discrete variables, and specifies the set of values that can be assumed. For instance, a discrete variable representing an RGB color can have a categorical parameter of ['red', 'green', 'blue']. This list can be of any length, and is not limited to strings.

Variable relationships

A relationship between two variables defines a function f that takes one variable as an input, and produces another variable as an output. To be more precise, if we consider a relationship between the variable a and the variable b, then it’s possible to compute b = f(a). In our system, this relationship is expressed as b ~ f(a).

We support two types of relationships:

  • Deterministic relationships, where f is a deterministic function. In this case, once the value of a is known, the value of b is known with certainty. For instance, if a and b are related by b ~ a + 10, and a = 5, then we can infer that b = 15.

  • Probabilistic relationships, where f is a probabilistic function. In this case, even when the value of a is known, the value of b is uncertain. For instance, if a and b are related by b ~ normal(mean=a, variance=10), and a = 5, then b has a normal distribution with mean = 5 and variance = 10.

Importantly, only probabilistic relationships make sense in our system, because it allows to express uncertainty. A variable b that is deterministically related to a variable a doesn’t contain any information that a doesn’t already contain. Therefore, we only allow probabilistic relationships in our system.

As a consequence, if we know the value of a, then we don’t know the value of b with certainty. However, we can represent our beliefs about the value of b with a probability distribution. This distribution can be arbitrarily complex, and is described by the distribution parameter, for instance distribution=normal(mean=a, variance=10).

In addition to a distribution, every relationship has a type parameter. This type can be either continuous or discrete, and specifies whether b is a continuous or a discrete variable. This information is redundant with the type of the distribution parameter, because we assume that a normal distribution always produces continuous variables, whereas a Poisson distribution always produces discrete variables. Nevertheless, explicitly specifying the type makes the system slightly more robust to errors.

A relationship between two variables defines a function f that takes one variable as an input, and produces another variable as an output. For 1878–1921, each year is divided into quarters, resulting in four index volumes per year. The March quarter indexes events from January through March; the June quarter, events from April through June; the September quarter, events from July through September; and the December quarter, events from October through December. The General Register Office created a second index for the years 1903–1921. This index is arranged by year and is available only at the office. Republic of Ireland, 1922–present: For the years 1922–1927, 1933, and 1966 to the present, the General Register Office’s copy of birth indexes is filed by year while the Family History Library’s microfilm copies (1922–1958) are all filed by quarter. Indexes for all other years and all other events through 1966 are by quarter. Northern Ireland, 1922–present: These indexes are quarterly, meaning there are four indexes per year.  These indexes provide: name, registration district, volume number, and a page number. This reference then can be sent to the General Register Office 1922-present to obtain a document or looked at 1922-1959 through The Family History Library or a Family History Center. Northern Ireland from 1922-1959: HAS NOT BEEN INDEXED  on familysearch.org under the Historical Records Portion as of 2011. Plans for this being indexed are not known. Ireland kept two sets of registrations, one local and the other national. This document describes the national indexes, not the local ones. Prior to the separation of Northern Ireland from the Republic of Ireland in 1922, all national civil registration records and indexes for the island were kept by the General Register Office in Dublin. Beginning in 1922 there were two General Register Offices, one in Dublin for the Republic of Ireland and one in Belfast for Northern Ireland. Irish civil registration indexes begin in 1845 for non-Catholic marriages. Civil registration indexes to births, deaths, and all marriages (including Catholic) begin in 1864. Indexes for all of Ireland continue from these beginning dates through 1921, when Northern Ireland and the Republic of Ireland became separate countries. The value of the spline approximation and the value of the inverse cumulative function is calculated internally at each step to minimize computations at the expense of memory. You will also want to read the FAQ. What are testbeds, projects, and experiments?

A testbed is a collection of nodes, switches, and links. These nodes can be scheduled and used as part of an experiment. We have a moderate-sized testbed in Utah, with just over 300 nodes. It also has 3 "emulated" nodes: these are NetBSD machines running an emulation environment so that hundreds of machines can be simulated on a few actual machines. The testbed at Utah is closely coupled with the testbed at Flux.

An experiment is a scheduled use of a testbed. You can swap in, which means you get immediate use of some nodes on a testbed. If the nodes are not available right away, you can queue your experiment so that you get nodes as soon as possible. You can also schedule your experiment in the future. See our tutorial for an example of how to create experiments.

A project is a collection of users that are allowed to work together. A project can have as few as 1 member (you!) or as many as several hundred. Only members of a project can create experiments that are "inside" the project; one useful reason for doing this is if you want another project member to be able to control (swap or terminate) your experiment. Project membership can be changed by users, or by the Testbed Operations staff. What kind of hardware is used for your nodes?

Currently, our Utah Testbed has about 300 PCs (most of which are diskful), 2 emulated PCs, 10 NetBSD machines, 7 FreeBSD machines, and 5 NetBSD Firewalls. The PCs are used as generic, multi-purpose nodes in an experiment. The NetBSD machines are used as operating system development boxes, for people interested in a full-blown OS environment (say, as an application server). The Firewalls act as IP filters/guards for experiments that include a "control net" (see the tutorial for more details). Finally, the emulated PCs are actually 4 Intel boxes (IBM 1U rackmounts) each running 100 emulated PCs. See the Hardware Overview page for a more detailed listing of the specifications for each type of node. What kind of OS do the nodes run?

The generic PC nodes can run a variety of operating systems subsets. The full list is: Linux (Redhat 7.1), FreeBSD 4.3, FreeBSD 4.7, Freebsd 4.8, NetBSD 1.5, and "RHL73-STD", which is Redhat 7.3 with our testbed modifications. The NetBSD OS machines (which are Intel x86 machines) run the NetBSD operating system. The FreeBSD OS machines run the FreeBSD operating system. The firewall machines run FreeBSD. What policies govern the use of the Testbed?

First, the Department of Energy (DOE) has paid for the Utah testbed, so it pays to be polite and not use the testbed for commercial gain. Keep in mind that we're very open about what "research" encompasses, but please ask us if you're unsure about whether your work constitutes research! Realistically, we do not have the resources to carefully ensure that no one is using the testbed for personal gain.

Also, we do not allow people to attempt to break into other people's experiments. If we catch people deliberately interfering with other experiments, they will have their ability to use our resources revoked.

We will use all available user and system IDs (email addresses and login names) to contact users who are using resources (such as nodes and network bandwidth) counter to the Testbed Policies.

Finally, our policies do change over time, normally in response to abuse or as necessary for the safe operation of the Testbed. You should familiarize yourself with the current policies. Here they are:

  • Main Policies
  • Security Policies
  • Widearea Node Usage Policies
  • PlanetLab Usage Policies Do you have a tutorial that shows me how to use the Testbed?

    Yes, we do! Here's the Tutorial. Do I need to write a proposal or have a testbed "project member" fill out any paperwork?

    Nope! We consider our proposal process to be "learning by doing." Here's how it works. First, you request an account. We ask you to answer a few questions so that we can get a feeling for the kind of research you are doing. You will get an account several days after you apply. When you start using the testbed, we will be able to examine your work, and help you out if you have any questions. If we think your project will benefit from a larger amount of support, such as the creation of a project web site, the ability to add other members, and/or a project publication listing, we will invite you to join an existing project or to create your own project. The project creation process requires both the principal investigator and Testbed Operations to agree to a simple set of guidelines.

    As a special case, if you are an undergraduate or graduate student, and you want to start using the testbed, please apply for a personal Emulab.Net project to which you will be the only member. We encourage you to update your personal project information page when you write a paper or thesis; lots of people read those pages! What if I'm a professor or administrator and I want to create a project for a class I'm teaching?

    Creating a class project is easy! Apply for a new project here. Indicate that you want to create a class project and we'll set it up for you with the proper privileges. Please use the project description to describe your class, including the name, syllabus, term, year, and meeting times. When your project is approved, we will configure it properly; you will then be able to add and remove users (students) from your project. See this tutorial for information on how to get started using the Testbed. How do I start using the Testbed?

    You can start by going to the "Start/Join Project" page. You may request to start a new project (a collection of users working on a particular research area) or join an existing one. If you're unsure, or are starting out with a small group or by yourself, please start a new project. If you are joining Emulab with a class using Emulab, please join the project specified by your instructor. If you have any questions about starting or joining a project, contact us at testbed-ops@flux.utah.edu.

    Note that we currently DO NOT require a "security question". If you forget your password, email us.
